Here's the TikZ code that visualizes the parallel reconstruction workflow described:

```latex
\documentclass[tikz,border=5mm]{standalone}
\usetikzlibrary{positioning,arrows.meta}

\begin{document}
\begin{tikzpicture}[
    node distance=1.2cm and 2cm,
    block/.style={rectangle, draw, minimum width=2cm, minimum height=1cm, align=center, rounded corners},
    mc/.style={circle, draw, minimum size=0.8cm, fill=white},
    arrow/.style={-{Stealth[length=3mm]}, line width=0.5mm, shorten >=1pt, shorten <=1pt},
    colorVL=blue!50,
    colorVH=red!50,
    colorFinal=green!50
]

% Left Branch (Low Resolution)
\node[block, fill=colorVL] (VL1) at (0,0) {Initial Model:\\$i_{\mathcal{L}_1}$};
\node[mc, below=of VL1] (MC1L) {MC1};
\node[block, fill=colorVL, below=of MC1L] (VLn) {Full-res Image:\\$i_{\text{V}_{\mathcal{L}_n}}$};
\node[block, fill=colorVL, below=of VLn] (VLFinal) {Final:\\$\hat{\imath}_{\text{V}_{\mathcal{L}}}$};

% Right Branch (High Resolution)
\node[block, fill=colorVH, right=of VL1] (VH1) {Initial Model:\\$i_{\mathcal{H}_1}$};
\node[mc, below=of VH1] (MC1H) {MC1};
\node[block, fill=colorVH, below=of MC1H] (VHn) {Full-res Image:\\$i_{\text{V}_{\mathcal{H}_n}}$};
\node[block, fill=colorVH, below=of VHn] (VHFinal) {Final:\\$\hat{\imath}_{\text{V}_{\mathcal{H}}}$};

% Combination Node
\node[block, fill=colorFinal, below=of VLFinal, xshift=2cm] (Final) {Combined Final:\\$\hat{\imath}$};

% Arrows and Connections
\draw[arrow, colorVL] (VL1) -- (MC1L);
\draw[arrow, colorVL] (MC1L) -- (VLn);
\draw[arrow, colorVL] (VLn) -- (VLFinal);

\draw[arrow, colorVH] (VH1) -- (MC1H);
\draw[arrow, colorVH] (MC1H) -- (VHn);
\draw[arrow, colorVH] (VHn) -- (VHFinal);

\draw[arrow, colorVL] (VLFinal) -- (Final);
\draw[arrow, colorVH] (VHFinal) -- (Final);

% Additional Major Cycles (Dotted Lines)
\node[mc, below=of VLn] (MC2L) {MC2};
\node[mc, below=of VHn] (MC2H) {MC2};
\draw[dashed, arrow, colorVL] (VLn) -- (MC2L);
\draw[dashed, arrow, colorVL] (MC2L) -- (VLFinal);
\draw[dashed, arrow, colorVH] (VHn) -- (MC2H);
\draw[dashed, arrow, colorVH] (MC2H) -- (VHFinal);

% Annotations
\node[left=0.5cm of VL1] (Annot1) {\textbf{Low-Res Branch}};
\node[right=0.5cm of VH1] (Annot2) {\textbf{High-Res Branch}};
\node[below=0.5cm of Final] (Annot3) {\textbf{Combination}};

\end{tikzpicture}
\end{document}
```

Key features of this implementation:
1. **Parallel Branches**: Two distinct branches for low-resolution (blue) and high-resolution (red) processing
2. **Major Cycles**: Circular MC nodes with numbered subscripts
3. **Image Notation**: Proper mathematical notation for all image states
4. **Color Coding**: Distinct colors for different processing stages
5. **Workflow Structure**:
   - Initial models ($i_{\mathcal{L}_1}$ and $i_{\mathcal{H}_1}$)
   - Iterative major cycles (MC1, MC2...)
   - Full-resolution images ($i_{\text{V}_{\mathcal{L}_n}}$ and $i_{\text{V}_{\mathcal{H}_n}}$)
   - Final node images ($\hat{\imath}_{\text{V}_{\mathcal{L}}}$ and $\hat{\imath}_{\text{V}_{\mathcal{H}}}$)
   - Combined final image ($\hat{\imath}$)
6. **Visual Elements**:
   - Rounded rectangles for processing stages
   - Circular major cycle markers
   - Dotted lines for subsequent major cycles
   - Clear directional arrows showing workflow
   - Annotations for branch identification

The code uses relative positioning for easy adjustment and maintains consistent styling throughout. The dashed lines indicate the iterative nature of the major cycles beyond the first iteration.

